Thought it sounded weirdly close to the Indo-European root, considering it's not an Indo-European language. Looked it up, and apparently, the Finnic root is a borrowing from Proto-Germanic *wīsaz ("wise"). So the word "viisaus" has basically the same origin as the English word "wisdom", and same goes for "viisas" and "wise".

But also, it has the same origin as all the other words in Indo-European languages which come from the Indo-European root (which was related to both knowing and seeing) from which this Germanic root comes.

This includes "wit", of course, but also the Latin root related to seeing, so : in English, the words "visible", "vision", "video", and many other words, the Romance words for "to see" : Italian "vedere", Spanish and Portuguese "ver", French "voir" (past participle -> vu, from which the noun "vue", from which English "view"), Romanian "vedea", etc.

It also includes Ancient Greek ἰδέᾱ, which "idea" comes from (the v/w element was dropped in this one), but also, interestingly enough, ῐ̔στορῐ́ᾱ (historíā, "history"), though it's harder to see (hehe get it?).

There's also Sanskrit वेद (véda, "knowledge", from which we derived "Vedic"), along with other Sanskrit words from the same root.

We get the Slavic root related to seeing as well, for example in the word for "to see" : Russian ви́деть (vídet'), Bulgarian ви́дя (vídja), Polish "widzieć", and so on.

That's just a sneak peak, there are many, many words I didn't mention, including in some Indo-European languages I didn't mention, like Albanian or Armenian, or any of the Celtic, Baltic, or Iranian languages...
